# {{lb|en|nuclear physics}} A [[torus]]-[[shape#Adjective|shaped]] [[chamber#Noun|chamber]] used in [[nuclear fusion]] [[research#Noun|research]] in which a [[plasma]] is [[magnetically]] [[confine]]d. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=E. P. Gorbunov|author2=K. A. Razumova|title=The Effect of a Strong Magnetic Field on the Magnetohydrodynamic Stability of Plasma and the Containment of Charged Particles in the ‘Tokamak’|journal=Soviet Atomic Energy|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=Consultants Bureau|month=November|year=1963|volume=15|issue=5|page=1105|issn=0038-531X|oclc=819039275|passage=Studies of electrodeless discharges in a strong longitudinal magnetic field, carried out on the stellarator and the "'''Tokamak'''", have shown that in such systems the plasma becomes unstable for currents appreciably les than the critical current of Shafranov-Kruskal.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=J. W. Lue|author2=R. W. Conn|title=Superconducting Toroidal Field Magnets for a Tokamak Engineering Test Reactor|editors=K. D. Timmerhaus and D. H. Weitzel|journal=Advances in Cryogenic Engineering|location=New York, N.Y.; London|publisher=[[w:Springer Science+Business Media|Plenum Press]]|year=1975|volume=21|page=41|oclc=912384789|location2=Boston, Mass.|publisher2=Springer|year2=2013|page2=41|pageurl2=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQDyBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA41|doi2=10.1007/978-1-4757-0208-8_6|isbn2=978-1-4757-0210-1|passage=A '''Tokamak''' engineering test reactor (TETR) will be an important component of any national or international program to achieve viable '''Tokamak''' fusion power reactors.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|chapter=Controlled Nuclear Fusion|title=Energy in Transition 1985–2010: Final Report of the Committee on Nuclear and Alternative Energy Systems, National Research Council|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[w:National Academies Press|National Academy Press]]|year=1982|page=390|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=V1bn2rxU-FsC&pg=PA390|isbn=978-0-309-03331-2|passage=Of magnetic fusion experiments, those in '''Tokamaks''' are closest to achieving the combination of confinement conditions needed for a reactor.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=D. Benningfield|title=Funds Requested to Speed Up Nuclear Fusion Experiments|editor=Ernstine Wheelock|magazine=[[w:The Alcalde|Alcalde]]|month=September–October|location=Austin, Tx.|publisher=The Ex-Students' Association of the {{w|University of Texas}}|year=1989|volume=78|issue=1|page=43|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=idcDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA43|column=1|issn=0002-497X|oclc=3952600|passage=Researchers use large doughnut-shaped vessels called '''tokomaks''' to try to achieve the critical temperature and density needed for fusion to begin. A '''tokomak''' uses powerful magnetic fields to contain hydrogen, which is heated to several million degrees. As the strength of the magnetic field increases, it squeezes the plasma, resulting in a higher temperature and density.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Raffi Khatchadourian|authorlink=Raffi Khatchadourian|title=A Star in a Bottle: An Audacious Plan to Create a New Energy Source could Save the Planet from Catastrophe. But Time is Running Out.|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/03/03/a-star-in-a-bottle|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205162338/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/03/03/a-star-in-a-bottle|archivedate=5 December 2018|magazine={{w|The New Yorker}}|date=3 March 2014|passage=Slowly, the solenoid—all one thousand tons of it—will be carried to the '''tokamak''' and lowered into the center of the vacuum chamber.}}

